Q.1.2. Use the ggplot() function to create the first layer of your plot using the life_expec DataFrame.

life_expec %>% ggplot()

Q.1.3. Add an aes() layer to your graph specifying Avg_Life_Expec as the dependent variable and Year as the independent variable.

life_expec %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Life_Expec))

Q.1.4. Add a layer to your graph to illustrate the relationship between Year and Avg_Life_Expec.

life_expec %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Life_Expec)) + geom_line()

Q.1.5. Create a new tibble, life_expec_filter, containing only rows for which the Race variable has the value “All Races,” and the Sex variable has the value “Both Sexes.”

life_expec_filter <- life_expec %>% filter(Race == 'All Races' & Sex == 'Both Sexes')

Q.1.6. Create a line graph that displays the relationship between Avg_Life_Expec and Year.

life_expec_filter %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Life_Expec)) + geom_line()

Q.1.7. Give your graph a descriptive title that communicates the goal of the visualization: “United States Life Expectancy: 100 Years of Change”

life_expec_filter %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Life_Expec)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "United States Life Expectancy: 100 Years of Change")

#### Q.1.8. Give the y-axis this label: “Average Life Expectancy (Years)”

life_expec_filter %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Life_Expec)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "United States Life Expectancy: 100 Years of Change",
        y = "Average Life Expectancy (Years)")

Q.1.9. Change the background color of your line graph to white.

life_expec_filter %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Life_Expec)) +
    geom_line() +
    labs(
      title = "United States Life Expectancy: 100 Years of Change", 
      y = "Average Life Expectancy (Years)"
    ) +
    theme(
      panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white")
    )
